c String serveSingleOkResponse(ServerSocket serverSocket) throws Exception {", "newText": "    private static HttpMethodDirectorClassLoader newHttpMethodDirectorClassLoader() {\n        URL location = HttpClient.class.getProtectionDomain().getCodeSource().getLocation();\n        return new HttpMethodDirectorClassLoader(new URL[] {location},\n                HttpMethodDirectorTest.class.getClassLoader());\n    }\n\n    private static String serveSingleOkResponse(ServerSocket serverSocket) throws Exception {"}, {"oldText": "            return requestLine;\n        }\n    }\n}\n", "newText": "            return requestLine;\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static final class HttpMethodDirectorClassLoader extends URLClassLoader {\n        private HttpMethodDirectorClassLoader(URL[] urls, ClassLoader parent) {\n            super(urls, parent);\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        protected Class<?> loadClass(String name, boolean resolve) throws ClassNotFoundException {\n            synchronized (getClassLoadingLock(name)) {\n                if (HTTP_METHOD_DIRECTOR_CLASS_NAME.equals(name)) {\n                    Class<?> loadedClass = findLoadedClass(name);\n                    if (loadedClass == null) {\n                        loadedClass = findClass(name);\n                    }\n                    if (resolve) {\n                        resolveClass(loadedClass);\n                    }\n                    return loadedClass;\n                }\n                return super.loadClass(name, resolve);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n"}]}
[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering class loading challenges**\n\nI’m grappling with the issue of class being package-private, which complicates the use of public APIs if loaded in isolation. It seems like I could trigger static initialization via Class.forName, but that has its limitations. Also, would the coverage consider the call stack here? If I load a fresh instance, it would execute, but I need to think through how to handle dependencies and potentially utilize a URLClassLoader. There are guidelines about avoiding direct reflection in tests, which makes this tricky!\n\n**Analyzing classloading without reflection**\n\nI’m considering the rules around avoiding direct reflection, and I wonder if Class.forName might help with dynamic loading instead. The guidelines suggest that if the application fundamentally relies on open-ended dynamic class loading, I should catch errors. I definitely need a custom classloader for a package-private class since there's no import. I’m also thinking about dependencies, particularly with HttpClient. However, I'm curious whether a URLClassLoader would even work with Native Image dynamic loading constraints.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_05bcafda8de1130f016a047c368d18819cbcbfeecbfdb3fc18\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqBHxEY81EOgz_ycoiVwzYf0xNiGzDNGyfrwWBTBRD0jrRTuR56KmPgs_b-vD8LsoM6VSRWvCU024Ch9iYu2hnEAOAQfITPHUetVdmf-B0E4eg4mUIuqlZ2yJ0R7Lm_rWDAWslwZ9OBi4bSTrBSpBM_jUueY5Y9sWtFxUmJqtK94b6xlk_PB1PUJ1kquxfMjU9g91y8zWBeQ-mcFHuEItbNGy8UMOmJ-fcfXklPXEDqfoC-kGxwoT8K3bC6cBvgOn_BzFMY5hZGDK6SSfsoKLGCHzQrEIo5Rq3c_vgwyigdD0TID6KPDleTT5z03G7bBBLu55qXfF6cHT5rjla6pW9sUkNcEpx0Y6ExxJ1utb5s_l8eS8RxukQoMVr8_o5C6D635dxZAiA7T2LD49LbaBNpxPJNcr5rEBsgyzyCxV_X4hX8PQ25G8aFHSB37YHq0X-4DXClnlQmJTtTm6CW8jY1OqJoYiVjyLoYjtJ4tovyKZRx15ZgHEAEbb6ruEGidQN2K1TocL9SAh2bRGe5DDuPbqL61kv-QsNbgP_gSow4nEsHPSIJgRILvNWcE8dIzb1o7c1GnrKuUFsoDcWQRCbBaaXHHOtsX